  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Defining AI Agent Roles**\n\nI\'m now focusing on defining the AI agents. The initial idea of two agents working sequentially is promising. Agent 1, the Researcher, will take user input and delve into web searches for relevant information, like current trends in a specific field. I\'m considering how this agent will handle diverse queries and ensure focused results.\n\n\n**Refining Agent Workflow**\n\nI\'ve decided on the agent workflow! Agent 2, the Editor, now takes structured findings from Agent 1 to create a concise digest. This will include an intro paragraph, bullet-point key findings, and a takeaway. Crucially, Agent 2 will rewrite, not just repeat, Agent 1\'s work. I\'ve also confirmed we can use the `@google/genai` library, with `gemini-2.5-flash` as the model, which is perfect!\n\n\n**Confirming Google Search Integration**\n\nI\'ve verified the `googleSearch` integration within the `@google/genai` library. The configuration is precisely `{ tools: [{ googleSearch: {} }] }` under `config`. Now, I\'m focusing on crafting a straightforward server route to execute both agents and shaping the API. The client will send a POST request to `/api/generate` with a `topic` string.\n\n\n**Defining JSON Schema**\n\nI\'m now focusing on the structured output for Agent 1. Using Gemini\'s structured output capabilities is a game-changer! I\'m defining a JSON schema for `findings`, ensuring consistent, structured data. Each finding will include source, a key point, and an excerpt, stored as an array of objects. I\'m exploring the best approach to implementing this schema with `responseMimeType` and `responseSchema`.\n\n\n**Defining Agent 2 Output**\n\nI\'ve finalized Agent 2\'s output schema! I\'m now structuring Agent 2\'s output as JSON, just like Agent 1, to make it super clean for my Glitch Art frontend. I will have an intro paragraph, three to five bullet points of key findings, and a concise takeaway. The JSON structure will be a consistent format, which will simplify the rendering process.\n\n\n**Finalizing Agent 2 Output**\n\nI\'ve nailed down the Agent 2 JSON output! It\'ll be an intro, 3-5 concise bullets (each a rewritten, polished point), and a sharp one-line takeaway. This structure allows for precise control in my Glitch Art frontend, with custom animations and perfect typography. Plus, I can return both the Researcher\'s findings and the Editor\'s digest, creating a step-by-step pipeline view for user inspection on the frontend!\n\n\n**Designing the Glitch Frontend**\n\nI\'m now diving into the frontend design! I envision a pitch-black terminal interface with cyan and magenta neon accents. Pixelated fonts like Share Tech Mono, VT323 and JetBrains Mono will give that retro-futuristic glitch aesthetic. I will include screen-tearing CSS animations, and UI interactions with sound effects, and make sure that it\'s highly readable and responsive. I\'ve successfully imported the Google Fonts and integrated them into the Tailwind configuration.\n\n\n**Implementing Server Endpoints**\n\nNow, I\'m shaping the server-side logic in `server.ts`! I\'m creating a POST endpoint, `/api/generate`, to run the two agents in sequence. I\'m also adding error handling to check for a missing `GEMINI_API_KEY`, providing a clear message if it\'s not set. I\'m keeping things modular, thinking I should organize the agent code within a separate file, `src/gemini.ts`.\n\n\n**Confirming Module Resolution**\n\nI\'m now deep-diving into the module resolution! It looks like TypeScript is correctly configured for ES Modules, with \"type\": \"module\" in `package.json`. Compiling the server with `esbuild` and specifying `--packages=external` makes everything super clean because my custom `src/` imports are directly bundled into the final `dist/server.cjs` file, preventing runtime resolution issues! I\'m really happy with this setup!\n\n```\n\n\n**Integrating Search Data**\n\nI\'m now integrating search data into Agent 1\'s structured output. The goal is a clear JSON schema with sources. I\'m focusing on handling `groundingMetadata` from the Google search and incorporating it into the findings. I\'m verifying if `googleSearch` works seamlessly with structured output in Gemini 2.5 to achieve this, which it does.\n\n\n**Defining Agent 1 Prompt**\n\nI\'ve crafted Agent 1\'s system instruction! I will ensure robustness by specifically defining the JSON schema to use. To guarantee correct output, I will also leverage the `responseSchema` for extra safety. Each finding now includes a source, a key factual point, and an excerpt, stored as an object within the `findings` array.\n\n\n**Crafting Agent 2 Prompts**\n\nI\'m now writing the system instruction for Agent 2, the Editor! It should take Agent 1\'s structured findings and rewrite them into a clean, concise Research Digest. The goal is to produce a JSON structure with an intro paragraph, a few bullet points, and a takeaway line. I\'m focusing on ensuring it\'s not just a regurgitation of Agent 1\'s work; it needs to be rewritten and polished.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 27
      nanos: 792745432
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
